{"key":"processedPost-15401801","value":{"id":15401801,"first":15400219,"last":15401803,"when":1321887774,"utime":"11/21/11 05:02 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Can spent substrate be used as spawn?<br /><br />Could I take the substrate that I had just harvested my 2nd or 3rd flush from and layer/mix it in a monotub?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />No.<br /><br />Not only is it 'spent', meaning the mycelium has slowed down or nearly stopped after producing fruits, a previously flushed substrate will have had billions of mold spores land on it.&nbsp; If you use this as spawn, you place those mold spores into fresh substrate, where they will germinate and grow much faster than the leftover mushroom mycelium, ruining your grow.<br /><br />One use for spent substrates is to place into a manure mix in your garden area, where they may or may not fruit again, but regardless, the fungi is beneficial to your plants.<br />RR","title":"Re: Silly yes or no question","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}